2. Enhanced Sentiment Analysis
  Weighted scoring – give more importance to recent articles or articles from authoritative sources.
  
  Aspect-based sentiment – instead of overall positive/negative, detect sentiment about specific topics (e.g., "earnings", "product launch", "regulatory issues").
  
  Use multiple models – compare FinBERT with VADER, TextBlob, or a custom fine-tuned RoBERTa.
  
  Confidence intervals – compute standard deviation or confidence bounds for the average sentiment.
  
  Neutral articles – currently neutral articles are ignored. Decide whether to include them with a neutral weight (0) or assign a small score based on confidence.
  
  Improve the "most relevant article" logic – your current method uses title sentiment and compares to the average. A better approach: find the article whose sentiment score is farthest from the average (or the most extreme sentiment) and link to it.

3. Data Storage & Historical Tracking
  Database – use SQLite (or PostgreSQL) to store each run: date, ticker, sentiment score, article links, etc.
  
  Time series analysis – plot sentiment over the past week/month to identify trends.
  
  Event correlation – detect if sentiment changes sharply before/after major news events (earnings, product launches).
  
  Example SQLite schema:
  
  sql
  CREATE TABLE sentiment_runs (
      id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
      ticker TEXT,
      run_date TIMESTAMP,
      avg_score REAL,
      sentiment TEXT,
      total_articles INTEGER,
      pos_count INTEGER,
      neg_count INTEGER
  );
  
  CREATE TABLE articles (
      id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,
      run_id INTEGER,
      title TEXT,
      link TEXT,
      sentiment_label TEXT,
      sentiment_score REAL
  );
